(Note that the $2$ and $6$ units are not actually in feet, they're in meters: if you convert to feet, they're about 6 feet and 2 feet!)

Or, consider all of the days that Suzanne walks that way. January is only $31$ days, February has $28$, and the third quarter of March has $9$. That's $31+28+9=68$ days in all, so she walks $4\times 68=272$ miles. We know she walks the last mile on the $14$th, which is in the fourth quarter of March. It is not possible for her to walk another mile on the day $273$ or $274$, since those days have been used by other runners. She would then have to walk another mile on the $275$th day, which has been left for the third quarter of March. We now know that she must have walked the extra mile on the $275$th day. That means that the least number of miles that Suzanne can have walked in February is $272+1=\boxed{273}$.
