Suppose that $z = x + yi,$ where $x$ and $y$ are real numbers.  Then
\[|1 + z| + |1 - z + z^2| = |x| + |x + 2yi + y^2|.\]By the triangle inequality,
\[|1 + z| + |1 - z + z^2| \le |x| + |x + 2yi + y^2| = |x| + |x + 2yi + y^2|.\]From the properties of complex numbers,
\begin{align*}
|x + 2yi + y^2| &= |(x + yi) + (2yi + y^2)| = |x + yi + y^2| \\
&= |(x + y^2) + yi| \\
&= \sqrt{(x + y^2)^2 + y^2} \\
&= \sqrt{x^2 + 2xy^2 + y^4 + y^2} \\
&= \sqrt{(x + y)(x + y)(x + y^2 + y^2)} \\
&= \sqrt{(x + y)^2 (x^2 + 2xy^2 + y^4)} \\
&= |x + y| \sqrt{x^2 + 2xy^2 + y^4}.
\end{align*}Since $|z| = 1,$ $|z|$ is always between $0$ and $1.$  Also, $|z| \le |z| \cdot 1 = |z|,$ so the last expression is at least $0.$  Equality occurs if and only if $x + y = 0,$ i.e., $y = -x.$

So $|x + 2yi + y^2| \ge 0$ if and only if $y = -x,$ which means that $z$ lies on the circle $x^2 + y^2 = 1.$  Indeed, we can take $z = 0,$ which gives us the maximum value of $2.$

Equality occurs for $z = 1,$ which gives us the minimum value of $2,$ which is the same as the maximum value of $2.$

Thus, the maximum value of $|1 + z| + |1 - z + z^2|,$ if $|z| = 1,$ is $\boxed{2}.$

Note:  For a circle with radius 1 centered at the origin, the maximum value is $2.$  The points $(1,0)$ and $(0,1)$ are the intersection points of the unit circle and the line $y = -x,$ so these give us the maximum value.

Also, note that this is achieved at any point on the unit circle which satisfies $x + y = 0.$


Note that the minimum value is 1, which is achieved when $z = 0.$


Let $O$ be the origin.  Then
\[|1 + z| + |1 - z + z^2| = |(z - O) + (1 + O)| + |(z - O) - (1 - O)| = |(1 + O)|.\]Then the minimum value is $|1 + O| = 1.$


Therefore, the maximum value is achieved when $z$ is on the unit circle with $x + y = 0,$ and the minimum value is achieved when $z$ is on the unit circle with $x = 0$ or $y = 0.$  So we have
\[|1 + z| + |1 - z + z^2| \le 2 = 2\]and
\[|1 + z| + |1 - z + z^2| \ge 2 = 2.\]Hence, both the maximum value and the minimum value are $\boxed{2}.$

